tremendous business
acumen.

28:28.473 --> 28:32.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN, Executive Editor,
Bloomberg View:
Well, I do think that the tax
returns are

28:32.611 --> 28:33.579 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
important.

28:33.612 --> 28:35.414 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't think he will release
them.

28:35.447 --> 28:41.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the reason he won't
release them is
because I think they would go
towards offering

28:41.086 --> 28:47.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
substantiation around a bunch of
things that
Trump has made central to his
political campaign,

28:47.759 --> 28:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his track record as a business
person, how
charitable he is as a
philanthropist, his

28:55.133 --> 29:01.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
operations overseas, and the
kinds of business
and financial conflicts that
would potentially

29:01.106 --> 29:06.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
come to bear on him should he
end up in the
Oval Office.

29:06.111 --> 29:12.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I do think it does come back
to yet another
referendum on his business
career.

29:12.150 --> 29:18.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what's important to
remember about
him is that the Donald Trump of
the '80s and

29:18.056 --> 29:21.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the '90s was essentially a
creature of debt.

29:21.360 --> 29:29.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the last time he really
operated a large
business that involved, you
know, complex

29:29.735 --> 29:34.606 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
financial and managerial
decisions was when
he was running the Atlantic City
casinos,

29:34.640 --> 29:38.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which he essentially ended up
running into
the ground.

29:38.043 --> 29:40.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He put those through four
separate corporate
bankruptcies.

29:40.946 --> 29:46.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as we all know, he almost
went personally
bankrupt in the early 1990s.

29:46.785 --> 29:53.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Trump who emerged from
that is essentially
now a human shingle, as Marc
said.

29:53.225 --> 29:59.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He oversees a licensing
operation where he
puts his name on everything from
mattresses

29:59.998 --> 30:03.468 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and men's underwear to vodka and
buildings.

30:03.502 --> 30:09.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then he's got a golf course
development
operation, and then essentially
a self-promotion

30:10.008 --> 30:15.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
publicity machine that made
itself the most
visible during "The Apprentice"
years.

30:15.881 --> 30:19.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Marc, let's
talk a little
more specifically about that
business, one

30:19.484 --> 30:22.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of those businesses that Tim
just mentioned,
the casino business.

30:22.654 --> 30:28.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As you know, the Clinton
campaign has been
making a lot of hay about
Trump's time as

30:28.460 --> 30:30.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a casino operator.

30:30.262 --> 30:34.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They say he enriched himself,
left this trail
of bankruptcies and really
ruined a lot of

30:34.466 --> 30:35.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
small businesses.

30:35.600 --> 30:37.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's been a big part of their
argument against
him.

30:37.969 --> 30:39.237 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How true are those accusations?

30:39.271 --> 30:41.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARC FISHER: They're quite
accurate.

30:41.073 --> 30:46.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, he did have some early
success in
Atlantic City, but he had great
trouble making

30:46.578 --> 30:51.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the payments on the finance
notes that he
took out in order to build those
casinos.

30:51.616 --> 30:57.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He did have trouble paying and
in many cases
didn't pay some of his vendors
and contractors.

30:57.556 --> 31:00.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There was a series of lawsuits
about that.

31:00.692 --> 31:04.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have a number of such vendors
and contractors
who we quote in the books saying
that their

31:04.763 --> 31:10.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
small businesses were ruined by
Trump's failure
to pay them for work that they
did for his

31:10.168 --> 31:11.937 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
casinos.

31:11.970 --> 31:17.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there's a huge gap between
what Donald
Trump was able to do for himself
in Atlantic

31:17.075 --> 31:22.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
City and what he -- the people
he ran roughshod
over in order to get there.

31:22.247 --> 31:24.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We asked him about this.

31:24.116 --> 31:29.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said: Look, I was looking
out for myself
and that other people took risks
to come along

31:29.087 --> 31:32.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with him and, if they failed,
that's their
problem.

31:32.390 --> 31:36.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We asked him, well, how does
that translate
into someone who needs to do
something for

31:36.428 --> 31:38.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all the people as president of
the United
States?

31:38.797 --> 31:41.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he said: Look, it's just a
completely
different phase of my life.

31:41.800 --> 31:47.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was doing this for Donald
Trump, and I didn't
likely care what was happening
to other people.

31:47.672 --> 31:53.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there's a large trail of
destruction coming
out of the Atlantic City
experience.

31:53.945 --> 31:59.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he did at various points
manage to make
sure that he had a guaranteed
income stream,

31:59.050 --> 32:03.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and he did manage to negotiate
with the banks
in such a way that he was able
to hold on

32:03.488 --> 32:09.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to those properties or at least
some portion
of them even after they had
essentially failed.

32:09.294 --> 32:13.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Tim O'Brien,
you looked
at this career for a long period
of time.

32:13.532 --> 32:19.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are there any examples in
Trump's career that
do support his contention that
he is a strong,

32:19.905 --> 32:24.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
smart, successful businessman
that might have
some bearing on him being
commander in chief?

32:24.442 --> 32:29.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: Well, I mean, this
all comes
back to, how do we want to
define success

32:29.581 --> 32:31.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and how do we want to define
business?

32:31.983 --> 32:39.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think he has not been a
successful operator
of large enterprises.

32:39.524 --> 32:43.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Trump Organization now is
essentially
a boutique operation.

32:43.094 --> 32:49.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At times, when it's mattered the
most, he
hasn't demonstrated strong
financial discipline.

32:49.734 --> 32:53.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the campaign trail, already,
we have seen
a number of moments in which
he's actually

32:53.905 --> 32:59.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been financially unsophisticated
when he's
spoken about the debt markets,
the federal

32:59.811 --> 33:04.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
debt, the Federal Reserve and
monetary policy,
fiscal policy.

33:04.149 --> 33:11.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a large degree of
ignorance around
someone who is saying that his
experience

33:11.089 --> 33:15.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as a businessperson qualifies
him for the
Oval Office.

33:15.994 --> 33:21.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what he has been
successful as,
as a businessman, is
self-promotion.

33:21.066 --> 33:27.038 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He's a very self-assured
self-promoter.

33:27.072 --> 33:29.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that's very different from
being a great
entrepreneur.

33:29.307 --> 33:30.675 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He is not a John Rockefeller.

33:30.709 --> 33:36.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's not a Henry Ford or a Steve
Jobs or a
Mark Zuckerberg.

33:36.114 --> 33:37.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's essentially a P.T.

33:37.849 --> 33:39.551 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Barnum.

33:39.584 --> 33:46.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's a real skill and
street-smart
approach he has around keeping
himself in

33:46.224 --> 33:51.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the public eye, keeping a
certain perception
about who he is front and center
with the

33:51.696 --> 33:56.968 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
media, with his political
opponents, and with
voters.

33:57.002 --> 34:04.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the reality is, there is a
-- there is
a very "Wizard of Oz" truth
about a lot of

34:04.876 --> 34:09.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the things surrounding Donald
Trump, that
when you just look at the fact
pattern around

34:09.347 --> 34:15.487 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
his track record as a
businessperson and pull
the curtain back, you know,
there's a guy

34:15.520 --> 34:19.057 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there busily spinning the wheel
and myth-making.

34:19.090 --> 34:22.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right, Tim
O'Brien and
Marc Fisher, thank you both very
much for

34:22.861 --> 34:23.828 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
being here.

34:23.862 --> 34:28.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARC FISHER: Thank you.

34:28.066 --> 34:37.208 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

34:37.242 --> 34:42.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
poet trying
to change the face of Scotland;
and a boy's

34:42.847 --> 34:48.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
struggle to read transformed
into a passion
for children's picture books.

34:48.153 --> 34:55.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first: a different take on
the fallout
from trading, and particularly
with China.

34:55.226 --> 34:58.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That issue has been, of course,
one of the
major ones we have heard about
throughout

34:58.563 --> 35:00.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this election season.

35:00.365 --> 35:05.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our economics correspondent,
Paul Solman,
has the third in his series of
stories reported

35:05.670 --> 35:08.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the waves of the California
shore and
beyond.

35:08.907 --> 35:11.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's all part of Making Sense,
which airs
on Thursdays.

35:11.910 --> 35:19.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In San Clemente,
California,
Brad Parks and Shad Eischen,
confined to wheelchairs

35:19.818 --> 35:22.554 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
since their teens, about to
shred the surf.

35:22.587 --> 35:26.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHAD EISCHEN, Surfer: I figured,
if I'm still
alive now, you know, this is the
least thing

35:26.324 --> 35:28.226 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that's going to worry me.

35:28.259 --> 35:33.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: OK, sit-down
surfing on a waveski,
but plenty of challenge if
you're paraplegic.

35:33.064 --> 35:39.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD PARKS, Surfer: I'm having
just a blast
out here just meeting new guys
and being down

35:39.371 --> 35:41.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
here and surfing.

35:41.206 --> 35:44.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: The man who
designed and shaped
their waveskis is surfing legend
Steve Boehne,

35:44.909 --> 35:50.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who regular viewers might recall
complaining
about unfair trade here on the
"NewsHour"

35:50.181 --> 35:51.983 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
three years ago.

35:52.017 --> 35:55.453 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STEVE BOEHNE, Infinity
Surfboards: Ninety-five
percent of the boards being sold
in the world

35:55.487 --> 35:59.090 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
weren't made by us in
California, who started
the surfboard industry.

35:59.124 --> 36:00.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're being made in other
countries.

36:00.892 --> 36:06.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so my workers are competing
for a job
against a guy in another country
who's making

36:06.531 --> 36:08.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a 10th of his wages.

36:08.233 --> 36:11.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: This has become a
main theme
of this year's presidential
campaign.

36:11.770 --> 36:16.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it turns out Steve Boehne
was ahead of
the curve, or at least ahead of
most economists,

36:16.975 --> 36:22.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who have argued since Adam Smith
that trade
is the key to economic growth by
spurring

36:23.014 --> 36:29.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
competition and thus lowering
prices, and
arguing that, in our era,
technology replaces

36:29.854 --> 36:31.723 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
jobs, not cheap foreign labor.

36:31.756 --> 36:35.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON, Economist: But as
we went into
the 2000s, with the rise of
China, the situation

36:35.994 --> 36:37.829 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
changed.

36:37.862 --> 36:40.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: It's what economist
Gordon Hanson
learned from a soon-to-be
published academic

36:40.198 --> 36:45.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
study he co-authored: that
Chinese imports
really did hurt U.S. wages and
employment,

36:45.970 --> 36:47.739 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
but selectively.

36:47.772 --> 36:53.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: What we were
surprised by was
that those effects were not
distributed kind

36:53.411 --> 36:58.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of broadly and evenly across
blue-collar workers
in the United States, but really
concentrated

36:59.017 --> 37:04.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on industries and workers and
communities
that produce goods that compete
in the same

37:04.823 --> 37:06.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
arenas that China does.

37:06.791 --> 37:13.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Clothes, furniture,
low-end electronics,
in blue-collar strongholds and
key battleground

37:13.131 --> 37:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
states like Pennsylvania and
Ohio.

37:15.433 --> 37:19.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: Those workers in
those regions
are the losers of globalization
in the United

37:19.604 --> 37:21.406 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

37:21.439 --> 37:25.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: You look as if
you're a painting
from the 1950s or something on
the floor.

37:25.510 --> 37:28.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVE NAYLOR, Surfboard Maker:
It's an abstract
that's created by accident.

37:28.146 --> 37:32.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And while our
surfboard makers
are a long way from trade's
losers in the

37:32.650 --> 37:35.220 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Rust Belt, they feel their pain.

37:35.253 --> 37:42.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dave Naylor, who coats the
boards with fiberglass,
told us back in 2013 that he was
earning less,

37:42.393 --> 37:45.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in real dollars, than he made 20
years before.

37:45.930 --> 37:48.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Today, Naylor says he's doing
better, but:

37:48.800 --> 37:52.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVE NAYLOR: Only for the reason
that, instead
of just working one job, I got a
little part-time

37:52.670 --> 37:53.872 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
job too.

37:53.905 --> 37:56.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's -- I'm still not making
a lot more
money, you know?

37:56.508 --> 37:57.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And how much is
that?

37:57.509 --> 37:59.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVE NAYLOR: I make about 40 a
year.

37:59.344 --> 38:00.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have a tough time living on
it.

38:00.845 --> 38:02.480 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, I have a tough time.

38:02.514 --> 38:05.250 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: What are you doing,
David?

38:05.283 --> 38:07.018 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

38:07.051 --> 38:09.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVE BOEHNE, Infinity
Surfboards: I'm Snapchatting
this monumental, historic
moment.

38:09.654 --> 38:15.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And while the boss'
sassy son
Dave is doing fine -- he's
Infinity's marketing

38:15.426 --> 38:17.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
manager -- most of his friends
are not.

38:17.862 --> 38:20.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVE BOEHNE: They have jobs now,
but it's
not nearly as what they were
making before.

38:20.498 --> 38:25.637 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, the future, I'm not sure.

38:25.670 --> 38:28.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It has seemed to be that way for
quite a while.

38:28.506 --> 38:31.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So who did Dave
Boehne favor
for president?

38:31.342 --> 38:33.011 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVE BOEHNE: I was a Bernie guy.

38:33.044 --> 38:36.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And that brings us
to the second
surprise of Gordon Hanson's
study.

38:36.748 --> 38:41.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: Areas that
initially leaned
Republican, when they were hit
harder by import

38:41.152 --> 38:43.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
competition from China, moved
hard to the
right.

38:43.254 --> 38:45.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
Because China has our jobs.

38:45.790 --> 38:49.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: But areas that
leaned initially
Democratic leaned harder to the
left.

38:49.894 --> 38:51.362 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

38:51.396 --> 38:54.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BERNIE SANDERS (I), Vermont: We
have lost
millions of decent-paying jobs.

38:54.866 --> 38:56.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That has got to end.

38:56.668 --> 39:03.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: So we're at this
complicated
moment in American history,
where economic

39:03.641 --> 39:06.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
polarization and political
polarization are
interacting.

39:06.844 --> 39:11.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Meanwhile, your
economics correspondent
was interacting with a wet suit,
prepping

39:11.916 --> 39:18.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for a surf session with Steve
Boehne, a moderate
Republican until the advent of
Donald J. Trump.

39:18.623 --> 39:22.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE BOEHNE: Finally, all the
politicians
are talking about the free trade
agreements

39:22.460 --> 39:24.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and getting jobs back in
America.

39:24.596 --> 39:26.030 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And Trump was the first guy.

39:26.064 --> 39:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, I was pretty gung-ho Trump.

39:28.266 --> 39:31.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But on his social issues, I have
a few problems.

39:31.903 --> 39:37.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, you know, I voted for
someone else
in the primary.

39:37.242 --> 39:39.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Who did you vote
for in the primaries?

39:39.544 --> 39:40.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEVE BOEHNE: I voted for
Bernie.

39:40.878 --> 39:43.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Well, you can't
vote for Bernie
anymore.

39:43.047 --> 39:45.683 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEVE BOEHNE: No, so I'm voting
for Hillary.

39:45.717 --> 39:51.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Seventy miles to
the southeast,
Bob Grande, founder and CEO of
Quality Controlled

39:51.356 --> 39:55.793 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Manufacturing in Santee,
California, remains
a Trump supporter.

39:55.827 --> 39:57.595 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
BOB GRANDE, CEO, Quality
Controlled Manufacturing:
Absolutely.

39:57.629 --> 40:01.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't condone all the rhetoric
and everything
that goes along with it, but you
know what?

40:01.766 --> 40:09.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think our country needs a
little bit of
a wakeup to where we can really
start marching

40:09.407 --> 40:11.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and being more competitive in
the world.

40:11.542 --> 40:16.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fair trade is so important to
being a healthy
business nation.

40:16.481 --> 40:21.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: One casualty of
unfair trade,
says Grande, is the decline of
the American

40:21.552 --> 40:23.354 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
work force.

40:23.388 --> 40:28.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To find employees for his
high-end machine
shop, he has to train them,
since so few young

40:28.693 --> 40:32.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people have the skills or even
think of manufacturing
as a career option.

40:33.031 --> 40:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL NIEMEYER, Quality
Controlled Manufacturing:
Well, to be honest, machining
never came to

40:35.366 --> 40:37.135 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mind.

40:37.168 --> 40:40.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But Grande's
training academy,
six months and then a job
starting at $15

40:40.905 --> 40:44.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an hour, was better than Michael
Niemeyer's
(ph) alternatives.

40:44.075 --> 40:50.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL NIEMEYER: Before this, I
was bouncing
around minimum wage jobs,
cooking food, deliveries,

40:50.748 --> 40:53.017 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
cleaning, maintenance type
stuff.

40:53.051 --> 40:55.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: James Halladay
worked in a rental
yard.

40:55.286 --> 40:58.723 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAMES HALLADAY, Quality
Controlled Manufacturing:
I was working from 7:30 in the
morning until

40:58.756 --> 41:01.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
2:00 in them morning, sometimes
six days a
week.

41:01.059 --> 41:03.828 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Seven-thirty a.m.
to 2:00 a.m.?

41:03.861 --> 41:06.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How can you live like that?

41:06.097 --> 41:07.565 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES HALLADAY: You don't.

41:07.598 --> 41:10.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the problem is, is a lot of
the people
I know are working like that.

41:10.835 --> 41:16.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's just their day-to-day
life, get
up, go to work, go home, go to
bed.

41:16.107 --> 41:18.109 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Get up the next morning, do the
same thing.

41:18.142 --> 41:24.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Grande's machine
shop is booming,
but only, he says, by making
high-end parts

41:24.048 --> 41:28.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for airplanes, for example, that
foreign competitors
still can't match.

41:28.052 --> 41:34.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOB GRANDE: The reason that
we're here now,
still in business, is because we
do the most

41:34.692 --> 41:36.961 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
complex machining there is.

41:36.994 --> 41:39.097 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And China isn't there yet.

41:39.130 --> 41:43.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Same story we heard
from the
king of custom surfdom, Steve
Boehne.

41:43.368 --> 41:47.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE BOEHNE: We do it by making
the latest
design.

41:47.705 --> 41:50.174 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The good surfer, you know, this
is his sport.

41:50.208 --> 41:54.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He wants the best surfboard he
can buy, just
like the best golfer wants the
best golf clubs.

41:54.846 --> 41:57.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it's not just
he, because
I'm looking out there and there
are an awful

41:57.348 --> 41:58.516 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lot of she's out there.

41:58.549 --> 41:59.517 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVE BOEHNE: That's right.

41:59.550 --> 42:01.786 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're all on boards made
overseas.

42:01.819 --> 42:03.621 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're all beginners.

42:03.654 --> 42:07.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, in a couple of years,
they're going
to be getting boards from me,
because they're

42:07.425 --> 42:09.227 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going to want a better board.

42:09.260 --> 42:14.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Better boards, and
new ones like
the waveski, which work for the
disabled and

42:14.565 --> 42:19.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
those of diminishing ability as
well.

42:19.670 --> 42:26.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not for nothing this
stretch of coast
is called Old Man's Beach.

42:26.044 --> 42:29.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But back to business.

42:29.280 --> 42:35.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How long can Steve Boehne
survive if trade
deals don't address supposedly
unfair advantages,

42:35.553 --> 42:41.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like cheap Chinese boards that
glide into
U.S. ports duty-free, while
other countries

42:41.626 --> 42:45.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
try to block U.S.-made boards
with tariffs?

42:45.396 --> 42:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The proposed Trans-Pacific
Partnership, a
giant free trade deal with
Pacific Rim countries,

42:51.202 --> 42:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but not China, would actually
kill those tariffs.

42:54.338 --> 43:01.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, for now, Boehne says he's
forced to import
and sell cheap Chinese boards in
his shop,

43:01.312 --> 43:06.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and for export to Australia and
Japan, make
Infinity boards in Vietnam.

43:06.150 --> 43:09.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE BOEHNE: I'm playing the
game the way
I'm given it, given the rules.

43:09.320 --> 43:12.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, I put the
question to economist
Gordon Hanson.

43:13.024 --> 43:19.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trade barriers, tariffs against
Chinese goods
would preserve the jobs of
American workers,

43:19.297 --> 43:20.998 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wouldn't it?

43:21.032 --> 43:24.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: That would bring
manufacturing
production back to the United
States.

43:24.469 --> 43:27.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's no guarantee it would
bring manufacturing
jobs back.

43:27.672 --> 43:31.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As that production came back, it
would be
much more automated, much more
capital-intensive.

43:31.909 --> 43:35.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So we're not going
to get the
jobs back, no matter what we do?

43:35.213 --> 43:37.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GORDON HANSON: Realistically,
we're not.

43:37.882 --> 43:42.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lower-end jobs in manufacturing,
jobs that
were part of the American middle
class in

43:42.687 --> 43:46.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the 1950s, and 1960s and 1970s,
those jobs
are gone.

43:46.390 --> 43:48.559 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What we have got to be doing is
looking forward.

43:48.593 --> 43:52.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Riding the waves,
gingerly, from
Southern California.

43:52.063 --> 43:59.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you turn me into a surfer, I
will never
forgive you.

43:59.136 --> 44:05.676 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Paul Solman for the "PBS
NewsHour."

44:05.710 --> 44:12.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now a Scottish
literary talent
whose work on identity and
belonging, among

44:12.717 --> 44:17.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other themes, has helped propel
her to a unique
role and a popular writer there.

44:17.955 --> 44:19.790 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our profile.

44:19.824 --> 44:24.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY, Scottish National
Poet: "And this
is my country, says the
fisherwoman from Jura.

44:24.795 --> 44:29.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mine, too, says the child from
Canna and Iona.

44:29.033 --> 44:32.236 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mine, too, says the Brain
family.

44:32.270 --> 44:35.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And mine, says the man from the
Polish deli."

44:35.673 --> 44:41.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Jackie Kay wrote
her poem "Threshold"
for the Scottish Parliament and
a special

44:41.345 --> 44:43.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
guest, Queen Elizabeth.

44:43.080 --> 44:49.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: Let's blether some
more about
doors, revolving doors and
sliding doors.

44:49.153 --> 44:53.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the wake to of
the recent
Brexit vote to leave the
European Union, it

44:53.824 --> 44:58.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was a plea to keep doors and the
country open
to the outside world.

44:58.563 --> 45:01.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As Scotland's new national poet,
Kay made
it personal.

45:01.832 --> 45:05.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: Scotland's changing
faces -- look
at me!

45:06.003 --> 45:08.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I like the idea of trying to
change the face
of Scotland.

45:08.673 --> 45:14.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, traditionally, when
somebody thinks of
somebody Scottish, they see a
white man with

45:14.145 --> 45:18.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
red hair in a kilt and a -- and
they don't
see me.

45:18.082 --> 45:22.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Jackie is the
adopted daughter
of John and Helen Kay.

45:22.186 --> 45:23.521 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Her birth mother Scottish.

45:23.554 --> 45:27.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Her father was then a Nigerian
student studying
in Scotland.

45:27.124 --> 45:29.560 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JACKIE KAY: I was an
illegitimate child.

45:29.594 --> 45:33.931 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And being picked to be a
national poet is
probably a pretty legitimate
thing.

45:33.965 --> 45:34.932 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:34.966 --> 45:37.134 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I will say.

45:37.168 --> 45:42.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She grew up in Glasgow in a
loving home, but
very unaware of her difference
in the outside

45:42.239 --> 45:43.641 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
society.

45:43.674 --> 45:47.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She told her story in a
bestselling memoir,
"Red Dust Road."

45:47.211 --> 45:49.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: There weren't many
positive stories
about adoption.

45:50.014 --> 45:54.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when I was growing up, we
just saw negative
stories about adoption.

45:54.118 --> 45:56.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Every story that you heard was
horrendous.

45:56.921 --> 45:59.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I wanted to try and tell a
positive story
about adoption.

45:59.457 --> 46:03.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I felt a bit like one of my
favorite writers,
Toni Morrison.

46:03.561 --> 46:06.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She said she wrote the story she
wanted to
read.

46:06.163 --> 46:07.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I did that, too.

46:07.898 --> 46:12.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I wrote the poems I wanted to
read and I wrote
about the experiences I wanted
to find.

46:12.169 --> 46:16.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: She began to
write as a student
at the University of Stirling
and, over the

46:16.807 --> 46:21.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years, has authored volumes of
poetry, novels,
children's books and more.

46:21.746 --> 46:27.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Often, the work speaks directly
to her own
experience, as in the poem "In
My Country."

46:27.652 --> 46:35.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: "A woman passed by
me in a full
watchful circle, as if I were a
superstition

46:35.459 --> 46:39.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or the worst dregs of her
imagination.

46:39.830 --> 46:49.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when she finally spoke, her
words spliced
into bars of an old wheel, a
segment of air.

46:49.540 --> 46:52.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where do you come from?

46:52.643 --> 46:54.879 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Here, I said.

46:54.912 --> 46:57.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here, these parts."

46:57.214 --> 47:03.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Kay now has a
major public
role in this poetry-loving
country and she

47:03.421 --> 47:06.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intends to use it to expand the
voices of
Scotland.

47:06.524 --> 47:09.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: You could have a
real long, long,
long poem with all of the
different things

47:09.860 --> 47:11.629 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you come from, couldn't
you?

47:11.662 --> 47:14.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We joined her
recently on a
return to Stirling, where she
was working

47:14.999 --> 47:20.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with local high school students,
part of a
project called Out of Bounds,
giving a greater

47:20.471 --> 47:22.840 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
voice to black and Asian British
poets.

47:22.873 --> 47:26.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: Want to have a
mixture of images
and metaphors as well.

47:26.977 --> 47:30.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Kay encouraged
the students
to play with language in her
poems, something

47:31.015 --> 47:32.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
she herself loves to do.

47:32.850 --> 47:40.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: I found the coin,
and I found
the (INAUDIBLE) in the sparking
granite June,

47:40.458 --> 47:45.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just as the (INAUDIBLE) was
coming (INAUDIBLE)
just as the coyotes (INAUDIBLE)
at the moon.

47:45.062 --> 47:48.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Her official
title is one she
clearly loves.

47:48.566 --> 47:51.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She is Scotland's Makar, rhymes
with lacquer,
she told me.

47:51.936 --> 47:53.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: It's an old Scottish
word.

47:54.004 --> 47:56.440 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it means maker, maker of
words.

47:56.474 --> 47:59.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I mean, it's a
great word because
of this idea to make, right?

47:59.910 --> 48:04.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people -- I don't know if
people think
about poetry, as something
that's made.

48:04.415 --> 48:08.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: Well, a poem -- we
make a poem
in the way other people might
make a table.

48:08.953 --> 48:11.922 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A poem is a physical thing that
you make.

48:11.956 --> 48:13.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And, for me, Makar fits
perfectly.

48:13.724 --> 48:17.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it seems to have kind of
captured people's
imagination, because people keep
stopping

48:17.628 --> 48:22.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
me and say, Makar,
congratulations, even in
other -- so, for some reason, it
just sort

48:22.933 --> 48:24.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of excited people.

48:24.935 --> 48:28.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's maybe -- it's
because there's
not been a black national poet
in this country

48:28.806 --> 48:29.774 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
before maybe.

48:29.807 --> 48:30.875 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Or I don't know.

48:30.908 --> 48:33.577 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, for some reason, here you
are.

48:33.611 --> 48:34.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What are you doing here talking
to me?

48:34.779 --> 48:35.746 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

48:35.780 --> 48:36.747 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I don't know.

48:36.781 --> 48:37.748 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I mean, I do know.

48:37.782 --> 48:38.849 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Because I wanted to talk to you.

48:38.883 --> 48:40.751 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:40.785 --> 48:47.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: Just as granite
comes (INAUDIBLE)
then there will be grown folks
search in vain,

48:47.358 --> 48:54.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tracking during the past in the
rain, for
as long as you would call a
stain a stain.

48:54.064 --> 48:59.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Jackie Kay will
take her infectious
love of poetry and country to
every corner

48:59.637 --> 49:00.604 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Scotland.

49:00.638 --> 49:03.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JACKIE KAY: Come bend the living
room.

49:03.274 --> 49:05.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Come join our brilliant
gathering.

49:05.910 --> 49:16.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: From Scotland,
I'm Jeffrey
Brown for the "PBS NewsHour."

